<p><!--
Conjectures for the name lost at the end of line A.1 include: Bhānugupta (#Basak_1919-20:142n1); Kumāragupta (Rao Bahadur H. Krishna Sastri in editorial note in #Dikshit_1923-24:193n1; #Sircar_1965:347n5 says Basak had suggested Budhagupta (but unless Basak made this suggestion somewhere other than #Basak_1919-20, Sircar is wrong about this). Sircar (ibid.) himself notes that Upagupta is also a possibility. #Agrawala_1983:123n6 mentions Viṣṇugupta along with the above possibilities; #Bhandarkar_1981:361 argues for Viṣṇugupta, with which #Goyal_1993:324-328 concurs.
--><pb

n="1r"/><lb
n="1"/>sa<unclear>mva</unclear> <num value="224"><g type="numeral">200</g> <g type="numeral">20</g> 4</num> bhādra di <num value="5">5</num> parama-daivata-parama-bhaṭṭāraka-ma<unclear>hā</unclear>rājādhirāja-śrī-<supplied reason="lost" cert="low"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->viṣṇu</supplied><lb
n="2" break="no"/>gupte pr̥thivīpatau tat-pāda-parigr̥hīte puṇḍravarddhana-bhuktāv upari<unclear>ka-mahārāja</unclear>sya<lb
n="3"/>rājaputtra-deva-bhaṭṭārakasya hasty-aśva-jana-bhogenānuvahamā<unclear>na</unclear>ke ko<unclear>ṭiva</unclear>rṣṣa-viṣa<unclear>ye</unclear> ca ta<lb
n="4" break="no"/>n-<choice><sic>niyuktakeha</sic><corr>niyuktaka Iha</corr></choice> viṣayapati-svayambh<choice><unclear>u</unclear><unclear>ū</unclear></choice>deve Adhiṣṭhānādhikaraṇa<supplied reason="lost" cert="low"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->m</supplied> āryyya-<unclear>na</unclear>gara-<unclear>śreṣṭhi</unclear>-<sic><unclear>ri</unclear></sic><unclear>bhu</unclear>pāla<lb
n="5"/>sārttha-vāha-sthāṇudatta-prathama-kulika-matidatta-prathama-kāyastha-skandapāla-puroge <unclear>sa</unclear>ṁvya<unclear>vaha</unclear>rati<!--
Agrawala has a "restored" [#mahā-] at the end of line A.2. This is not found either in Basak or in Bhandarkar and Agrawala does not cite any evidence for this. I can't tell from the facsimiles if there may have been any further characters; I stick with Bhandarkar.
--><!--
The correction of niyuktakeha in A.4 is doubtful. Agrawala notes that Basak had suggested °yuktake iha but this is "unnecessary." See also line A.3 of IN00046.
--><!--
In A.4 Bhandarkar reads svayambhū. Agrawala reads svayambhu and notes that Basak had suggested correcting to svayambhū. Given the condition of the plate, I'm noting this as an ambiguous reading.
--><!--
The m supplied after adhikaraṇa in A.4 is probably an editorial addition, not a guess at an illegible character. Compare line A.3 of IN00046. Leaving it as conjecturally read rather than as added for the time being.
--></p>
<p><lb
n="6"/>Āyo<unclear>dhya</unclear>ka-kula-puttrak<sic>a-A</sic>mr̥tadevena vijñāpitam<supplied reason="subaudible">.</supplied> iha viṣaye samudaya-bāhyāprahata-khila-<unclear>kṣe</unclear>ttrā<lb
n="7" break="no"/>ṇāṁ tri-dīnārika-kulya-vāpa-vikrayo nuvr̥ttaḥ<supplied reason="subaudible">.</supplied> tad arhatha matto dīnārān upasaṁgr̥hya man-mātuḥ <unclear>pu</unclear>ṇyā<lb
n="8" break="no"/>bhivr̥ddhaye Atrāraṇye bhagavataḥ śvetavarāha-svāmino deva-kule khaṇḍa-phuṭṭa-prati<unclear>saṁ</unclear>skā<unclear>ra-ka</unclear><lb
n="9" break="no"/>raṇāya bali-caru-sa<sic>tr</sic>a-pravarttana-gavya-dhūpa-puṣpa-prāpaṇa-madhuparkka-dīpādy-upa<unclear>yo</unclear>gā<unclear>ya</unclear> ca<lb
n="10"/>Apradā-dharmmeṇa tāmrapaṭṭīkr̥tya kṣetra-stoka<sic>n</sic> dātum iti<!--
For phuṭṭa see also IN00061 and IN00062.
--><!--
In A.7 Bhandarkar prints tridīnārika; Agrawala prints tridīnārikya and emends to traidīnārikya. Need to check this on a good facsimile or the original.
--></p>
<p>yataḥ prathama-pustapāla-nara<unclear>na</unclear>ndi<lb
n="11" break="no"/>-gopadatta-<unclear>bhaṭa</unclear>nandinām-avadhāraṇayā yuktatayā dha<unclear>rmmādhi</unclear>kāra-<unclear>bu</unclear>ddhyā vijṇāpita<supplied reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->ṁ</supplied> <unclear>no</unclear> kāry<unclear>o</unclear><lb
n="12"/>viṣaya-patinā kaścid virodhaḥ keva<unclear>laṁ</unclear> śrī-parama-bhaṭṭāraka-pādānā<supplied reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->ṁ</supplied> dharmma-<unclear>pha</unclear><supplied reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->la-ṣa</supplied><lb
n="13" break="no"/>ḍ-bhā<supplied reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->gā</supplied>vāp<unclear>t</unclear>i<supplied reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->ḥ</supplied><supplied reason="subaudible">.</supplied><!--
In A.11 Agrawala puts square brackets around the second ta of yuktatayā. Bhandarkar does not show this as unclear, so Agrawala may have intended the brackets as a deletion mark.
--><!--
In A.11-12, I follow Bhandarkar. Agrawala (after Sircar?) has nā[#ttra*] [#vi*]<lb
/>ṣaya-patinā[#ṁ].
--><!--
Line A.13 is engraved below the end of line A.12
--><!--
In A.12-13, I again follow Bhandarkar. Agrawala (after Sircar?) has pādena dharmmapa(ra)<lb
/>(tāvāpti)[#ḥ].
--></p>
<p><pb

n="1v"/><lb
n="14"/>Ity anenāvadhāraṇā-krameṇa Etasmād amr̥tadevāt pañcadaśa dīnārān upasaṁgr̥hya Etan-mātu<supplied reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->ḥ</supplied> <lb
n="15"/>Anugraheṇa svacchandapāṭake <unclear>rddha</unclear>ṭī-prāveśya-lavaṅgasikāyāñ ca vāstubhis saha kulya-vāpa-dvayaṁ <lb
n="16"/>sāṭuvanāśramake pi vāstunā saha kulya-vāpa Ekaḥ paraspatikāyāṁ pañca-kulya-vāpakasyotta<unclear>re</unclear>ṇa <lb
n="17"/>jamvū-na<supplied reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->dyā</supplied>ḥ pūrvveṇa kulya-vāpa Ekaḥ pūraṇavr̥ndikaharau pāṭaka-pūrvveṇa kulya-vāpa Ekaḥ<supplied reason="subaudible">.</supplied> Ity evaṁ khila-kṣettra<lb
n="18" break="no"/>sya vāstunā saha pañca kulya-vāpāḥ Apradā-dharmmeṇa bhaga<supplied reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->va</supplied>te śvetavarāha-svāmine śaśvat-kāla-bhogyā dattāḥ<supplied reason="subaudible">.</supplied> <lb
n="19"/>tad uttara-kālaṁ saṁvyavahāribhiḥ devabhaktyānumantavyāḥ<supplied reason="subaudible">.</supplied> Api ca bhūmi-<unclear>dā</unclear>na-saṁvaddhāḥ ślokā bhavanti<!--
In B.6 Bhandarkar prints saṁvadhāḥ and corrects to sambaddhāḥ. Agrawala prints samvaddhāḥ and corrects to sambaddhāḥ. The original may have anusvāra or m, and ddh or plain dh - need to check.
--></p>
<lg n="1" met="anuṣṭubh">
<l n="a"><lb
n="20"/>sva-dattāṁ para-dattām vā</l>
<l n="b">yo hareta vasundharāṁ</l>
<l n="c">sa viṣṭhāyāṁ k<sic>ri</sic>mir <sic>bhbh</sic>ūtvā</l>
<l n="d">pitr̥bhis saha pacyate<!--
In B.7 Bhandarkar has krimir bbhūtvā; Agrawala has bhbhūtvā and explicitly corrects to rbbh (not to standard rbh), also noting that Sircar's reading is rbhbhutvā.
--></l>
</lg>
<lg n="2" met="anuṣṭubh">
<l n="a">vahubhir vvasudhā dattā</l>
<l n="b"><lb
